# Intuition
This is an very simple question that involves iterating through the given list.

# Approach
Here is a brief pseudocode:
<ul>
<li>Iterate over the list one element at a time</li>
<li>If the element is equal to target, subtract it and store the result.</li>
<li>Check the result with the previous results and see if the new result is smaller.</li>
<li>update the result and return it</li>
</ul>

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
  This is a very easy question with a very basic approach. However, it took me 30 minutes because i couldn't understand the question. Then after debugging i finally understood the question. So on average this should take about 1 minute to do, maybe less

- Space complexity:
  I tried making the program use as much less memory as possible but it still takes a lot.

# Code
```
#include<limits>
class Solution {
public:
    int getMinDistance(vector<int> &a, int target, int start)
    {
        int i = 0;
        int prev = std::numeric_limits<int>::max();
        for (int x : a)
        {
            if (x == target)
            {
                int  p = std::abs(i -start);
                if (p < prev)
                {
                    prev = p;
                }
            }
            i++;
        }
        if (prev == std::numeric_limits<int>::max())
        {
            // nothing found
            return 0;
        }
        return prev;
    }
};
```

