solutions.content:
## Step 1: repeate finding next greater permutaiton k times to find k-th smallest wonderful number.
To find next greater permutation see, https://leetcode.com/problems/next-permutation/
Time `O(Nk)`, space `O(1)`

## Step 2: find the minimum adjacent swaps required to make two permutations A and B identical.
1. Create integer array `X` where `X[i]` is the smallest index of remaining `A[i]` in B, i.e. `X[i] = j` where `B[j] == A[i]` and `j` is as small as possible.
To do that, we can put B's element to index mapping into a `Map<Character, Queue<Integer>>`, and iterate over `A[i]` to dequeue the smallest index in `map.get(A[i])`
2. Count number of inverted pairs in X, this can be done similar to merge sort in `O(NlogN)` time.
Time `O(NlogN)`, space O(N)

Overall time complexity is `O(N(k + logN))`, space `O(N)`


```java
class Solution {
    public int getMinSwaps(String num, int k) {
        // find k-th smallest wonderful number
        String s = num;
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            s = nextGreaterPermutation(s);
        }
        return getMinSwaps(num, s);
    }

    private String nextGreaterPermutation(String num) {
        char[] A = num.toCharArray();
        // Find last i so that A[i] < A[i + 1]
        int i = A.length - 2;
        while (i >= 0 && A[i] >= A[i + 1]) {
            i--;
        }

        // swap A[i] with the smallest A[j] > A[i] where j > i
        int j = i;
        while (j + 1 < A.length && A[j + 1] > A[i]) {
            j++;
        }
        swap(A, i, j);
        // sort A[i+1:-1]
        reverse(A, i + 1, A.length - 1);
        return String.valueOf(A);
    }

    private void swap(char[] c, int i, int j) {
        char tmp = c[i];
        c[i] = c[j];
        c[j] = tmp;
    }

    private void reverse(char[] c, int start, int end) {
        while (start < end) {
            swap(c, start++, end--);
        }
    }

    // Count minimum number of adjacent swaps needed to make two permutations identical
    private int getMinSwaps(String a, String b) {
        int N = a.length();
        Map<Character, Queue<Integer>> charToBIdx = new HashMap<>();
        for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
            charToBIdx.computeIfAbsent(b.charAt(j), ignored -> new LinkedList<>()).offer(j);
        }

        int[] X = new int[N];
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
            X[i] = charToBIdx.get(a.charAt(i)).poll();
        }
        return getMinSwapsToSort(X, 0, N - 1);
    }

    // sort A[start...end] and return minimum adjacent swaps required
    private int getMinSwapsToSort(int[] A, int start, int end) {
        if (start >= end) {
            return 0;
        }

        int mid = start + (end - start) / 2;
        int res = getMinSwapsToSort(A, start, mid) + getMinSwapsToSort(A, mid + 1, end);

        // Two pointer count inverted pairs between left and right sorted subarrays
        int[] left = Arrays.copyOfRange(A, start, mid + 1);
        int[] right = Arrays.copyOfRange(A, mid + 1, end + 1);
        int l = 0;
        int r = 0;
        int i = start;
        while (l < left.length || r < right.length) {
            if (r >= right.length || l < left.length && left[l] <= right[r]) {
                res += r; // numbers in the right subarray that's smaller than A[l] is equal to the steps r pointer
                // has advanced
                A[i++] = left[l++];
            } else {
                A[i++] = right[r++];
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

