# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This problem is like a follow-up to the classic "Next Permutation" problem.
If you haven't solved "Next Permutation" yet, I would you recommend you to try it:
[https://leetcode.com/problems/next-permutation/]()

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Assuming you have followed the "Next Permutation" approach k times. We come to the swapping part.
It is efficient to simply use the greedy swapping as our time complexity is not hindered by it and also it is very easy to implement.

Simply, whenever you encounter mismatching elements in the two strings, keep a pointer at that element in string 2 and move a pointer on string 1 until you reach the string 2's element in string 1. Then keep swapping the adjacent elements till the initial pointer's position.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n*k)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n) to store a copy of the kth permutation of given number string.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minswaps(string s1, string s2)
    {
        int n=s1.size();
        int ctr=0;
        int i=0;
        while(i<n)
        {
            int j=i;
            if(s1[i]!=s2[i])
            {
                int j=i;
                while(s1[j]!=s2[i])
                    j++;
                while(j>i)
                {
                    swap(s1[j], s1[j-1]);
                    j--;
                    ctr++;
                }   
            }
            i++;
        }

        return ctr;
    }
    int getMinSwaps(string num, int k) 
    {
        string arr=num;
        int N=arr.size();
        while(k--)
        {
            int index=-1;
            for(int i=N-1; i>=1; i--)
            {
                if(arr[i]>arr[i-1])
                {
                    index=i-1;
                    break;
                }
            }

            if(index!=-1)
            {
                int p=index+1;
                for(int i=index+1; i<N; i++)
                {
                    if(arr[i]>arr[index])
                    {
                        if(arr[i]<arr[p])
                            p=i;
                    }
                }

                int t=arr[index];
                arr[index]=arr[p];
                arr[p]=t;
            }

            index++;
            sort(arr.begin()+index, arr.end());
        }

        return minswaps(num, arr);  
    }
};
```

