Well, I kind of forgot **next_permutation**  function existed, so had to make something that's still polynomial (even tho not nearly as fast as next_permutation). 

**PART1**: finding the kth permutation
We start from the the last digit of **num** and keep going left and adding numbers to **dp array** until we find such number **x** that is smaller than **at least 1** previously added numbers. then, we add the first number that is bigger than x (which is O(1) since the size of tracking array is always N =10) then swap it with x. 

After that we sort the numbers to the right of swapped number to ensure that the new number is bigger than the previous one, but as small as possible. This can be done via **count sort** since all the characters are numbers from 0-9, which leads to linear time sorting.

We repeat this process k times.
I think the complexity becomes O(N * K)

**PART 2**: finding minimum swaps
Well, this is pretty straight forward and there are plenty of great explanations in the discussion so I won't comment on this one. This runs in O(N^2) time I think.

