Probable internal implementation of `next_permutation` (just for fun)
```
void next_permutation(string& s) {
	auto it = is_sorted_until(rbegin(s), rend(s));
    if(it != rend(s)) swap(*it, *upper_bound(rbegin(s), it, *it));
    reverse(rbegin(s), it);
}
```
After that traverse both strings (original one and kth permutation one)
if it any position they differ. mark that position and find the number in other string,
Means that .. suppose 
string is `s = "5489355142"`
```
	5 4 8 9 3 5 5 1 4 2  => original string
	5 4 8 9 3 5 5 4 2 1  => kth next permutation
	. . . . . . . *      => differing position (1 != 4)
	we find   1 (element from top string) in bottom string .
	in bottom string it is present at the end (last element of bottom string is 1)

	we mark this position as pos
	Now, we know that swap occurred between i and pos.
	run a loop from i to pos and swap s[pos] and s[pos - 1] and increase swap count
	return count
```
