**Sweep Line Algorithm**:
Create a new class called Event. Each event has\xA0`[value,type,additionValue]`.

We can combine the intervals and queries arrays into one array of events.

Then sort the array of events base on value (if values are the same, sort by type)

Iterate through events array:
1. If the event is the left of the interval, add it to the TreeMap<length of the interval, right of the interval> which is sorted by the length of the interval
2. If the event is the right of the interval, means we need to close the interval. Remove one from the TreeMap.
3. If the event is the query, look at the top of the TreeMap to get the smalleset interval.

```
class Solution { 
    class Event{
        int value;//left, right or query value
        int type;//0 - interval left ; 1 - queries ; 2 - interval right
        int additionValue;//right or left or index of the query

        public Event(int value, int type, int additionValue){
            this.value = value;
            this.type = type;
            this.additionValue = additionValue;
        }
    }

    public int[] minInterval(int[][] intervals, int[] queries) {
        //base case
        if(intervals == null || intervals.length == 0 || queries == null || queries.length == 0) return new int[0];

        int numOfQueries = queries.length;
        int numOfIntervals = intervals.length;

        int[] result = new int[numOfQueries];

        List<Event> eventList = new ArrayList<>(numOfIntervals * 2 + numOfQueries);
        int i = 0;
        while(i < Math.max(numOfQueries, numOfIntervals)){
            if(i < numOfQueries) {
                eventList.add(new Event(queries[i], 1, i));//1 - query
            }
            if(i < numOfIntervals){
                int left = intervals[i][0];
                int right = intervals[i][1];
                eventList.add(new Event(left, 0, right));//0 - left
                eventList.add(new Event(right, 2, left));//2 - right
            }
            i++;
        }

        //sort the eventList by value (if values are the same, sort by type)
        Comparator<Event> cmp = new Comparator<>(){
            @Override
            public int compare(Event a, Event b){
                if(a.value == b.value) return a.type - b.type;
                else return a.value - b.value;
            }
        };
        Collections.sort(eventList, cmp);

        TreeMap<Integer, Integer> lengthSortedMap = new TreeMap<>();
        int numOfQueryProcessed = 0;
        for(Event e : eventList){
            if(e.type == 0){
                //interval start (open the interval)
                lengthSortedMap.put(e.additionValue - e.value + 1, e.additionValue);//length, right value
            } else if(e.type == 2){
                //interval end -> remove the start (close the interval)
                lengthSortedMap.remove(e.value - e.additionValue + 1, e.value);
            }
            else {
                //query
                if(!lengthSortedMap.isEmpty()){
                    result[e.additionValue] = lengthSortedMap.firstEntry().getKey();
                    numOfQueryProcessed++;
                } else result[e.additionValue] = -1;
            }
            if(numOfQueryProcessed == numOfQueries) break;//processed all queries, break the loop
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

