solutions.content:
Let us first start with the naive way. We want to use some sort of a Data Structure that supports segment queries [a,b] , so our Intervals are satisfied. Moreover, we want on each point inside that interval to have the minimum range of all the queries that contain said point. For this reason we can use a Segment Tree.
The segment tree will contain 1e7+1 elements, (the maximum possible value we may get) and then we ll just Query each point seperately to form our final result.
The code would look something like this

```
	S=new SegmentTree(0,1e7+1) //create the segment tree with the appropriate range
	for(let [a,b] of Intervals)
	//set each point in [a,b] to have the minimum b-a+1 of the queries that contain it
		S.rangeSet(a,b, b-a+1) 
	return Q.map( value=> S.pointQuery(value) ) //just query each point for the final result
```

Unfortunately the values inside my Queries can go up to 1e7+1, which is huge, and this will give us a Memory Limit Exceeded error. We can, however, remedy that without storing all of the potential values inside the segment tree. Instead, we can use a segment tree that stores Q.length elements, or rather 1 for each element of Q. The thing is that rangeSetting now becomes tricky, as we ll need to find which elements lie inside [a,b] so we can update them correctly. However, we need to keep in mind that we re dealing with a Sorted version of Q because everything inside the Segment Tree is always sorted. Therefore a simple binary search would yield us with the actual indices that need to be updated inside the Segment Tree. 
More specifically we will be looking for the Smallest index of Q that's bigger than or equal to a. In the same manner we will be looking for the BIGGEST index of Q that's smaller than or equal to b. Then we will have to rangeSet these indices instead, as these correspond to the interval we re currently examining. The code would then look something like this:

```
	S=new SegmentTree(0,Q.length+1)
	for(let [a,b] of Intervals)
		S.rangeSet( binarySearchSmall(Q , a), binarySearchBig( Q,b) , b-a+1)
	return Q.map( value=> S.pointQuery ( SORTED_INDEX_OF(value) ) )  
	//remember that after sorting, each  value inside Q has a new index, 
	//which we will be using to access that element inside the Segment Tree.
```

I will now provide the full code of the segment Tree approach. The implementation is simply a Segment Tree that supports range updates and and PointQueries whose details can be easily found online. 

```

let bisect_left=(A,element)=>{
    let lo=0,hi=A.length-1,res=Infinity
    while(lo<=hi){
        let mid=lo+hi>>1
        if(A[mid][0]<element)
            lo=mid+1
        else
            res=Math.min(res,mid),
            hi=mid-1
    }
    return res
}
let bisect_right=(A,element)=>{
    let lo=0,hi=A.length-1,res=-Infinity
    while(lo<=hi){
        let mid=lo+hi>>1
        if(A[mid][0]>element)
            hi=mid-1
        else
            res=Math.max(res,mid),
            lo=mid+1
    }
    return res
}
class ISTNode{
    constructor(l,r){
        this.l=l,this.r=r
        this.leftChild=this.rightChild=null
        this.val=Infinity
    }
    extend(){
        if((!this.leftChild )&& (this.l!==this.r)){
            let mid=this.l+this.r>>1
            this.leftChild=new ISTNode(this.l,mid)
            this.rightChild=new ISTNode(mid+1,this.r)
        }
    }
    rangeUpdate(L,R,val){
        if(L<=this.l&& this.r<=R){
            this.val=Math.min(this.val,val)
            return
        }
        if(L>this.r||this.l>R)
            return
        this.extend()
        this.leftChild.rangeUpdate(L,R,val)
        this.rightChild.rangeUpdate(L,R,val)
    }
    pointQuery(x,minsofar=Infinity){
        if(!this.leftChild)
            return Math.min(minsofar,this.val)
        if(this.leftChild.r>=x)
            return this.leftChild.pointQuery(x,Math.min(minsofar,this.val))
        else
            return this.rightChild.pointQuery(x,Math.min(minsofar,this.val))
    }
}

var minInterval = function(I, Q) {
    let n=Q.length,S=new ISTNode(0,n+1), Queries=[...Q]
    Queries=Queries.map((d,i)=>[d,i]).sort((a,b)=>a[0]-b[0])
    for(let [a,b] of I)
        S.rangeUpdate(bisect_left(Queries,a),bisect_right(Queries,b),b-a+1)
    for(let i in Queries){
        let [val,originalIdx]=Queries[i]
        Q[originalIdx]=S.pointQuery(i)
        if(Q[originalIdx]===Infinity)
            Q[originalIdx]=-1
    }
    return Q
};
```
Time Complexity is O( (n+Q) logQ ) and Space Complexity is O(4\*Q)

A more elegant approach is a Union Find Data structure as proposed in the top posts. The whole idea is that, for each element we have 2 properties. The first is its final result, meaning the length of the smallest interval that contains it. We will call this feature the element's color. The second, is a pointer to the first element on its right side that is not yet painted. One needs to notice that an element can only be painted once, so the first time it is painted has to be the minimum range interval that contains it. After an element is painted, its parent is updated as the first element on its right side that is unpainted, and we achieve is through the "find" operation of a DSU. So then the battle plan becomes:
* Sort the Intervals in ascending Range, so that the first time a range is set, it has to be the smallest one
* Update each range accordingly
* Build the result

So the code would look something like :
```
 let colors=[...Array(1e7+1)],
	 parent=[...Array(1e7+1)].map((d,i)=>i) //set each parent as the element itself,
	 find=(x)=>x===parent[x]?x: parent[x]=find(parent[x]) //the DSU find operation + path compression
 Intervals.sort((a,b)=> a[1]-a[0] - ( b[1] -b[0]) ) 
 for(let [a,b] of Intervals){
	 let start=find(a)
	 while(start<=b)
		 colors[start]=b-a+1,
		 parent[start]=start+1,
		 start=find(start)
 }
return Q.map((d,i)=>colors[d]) 
```

However we seem to be having the exact same problem as before. Due to the huge size of our initial array we get MLE. Now though, we know how to combat this by using a "proxy" DSU only for the element of Q that we aready have. The logic is exactly the same with the Segment Tree approach and the 2 binary searches.
Here follows the code that gets a clean AC.

