First sort the intervals based on their sizes.
Then record the size of each index in an interval to be the interval size;
if the sizes[i] is already recorded,  make i jump to ending[i]+1 and start counting from there.
```
class Solution {
    public int[] minInterval(int[][] intervals, int[] queries) {
        Arrays.sort(intervals, (a,b)->((a[1]-a[0]-(b[1]-b[0]))));
        int[] sizes = new int[10000000];
        int[] ending = new int[10000000];
        for (int[] interval: intervals) {
            for (int i = interval[0]; i<=interval[1]; i++) {
                if (sizes[i]>0) {
                    i = ending[i];
                } else {
                    sizes[i] = interval[1]-interval[0]+1;
                    ending[i] = interval[1];
                }
            }
        }
        int[] res = new int[queries.length];
        for (int i=0; i<queries.length; i++) {
            res[i] = sizes[queries[i]];
            if (res[i]==0) res[i]=-1;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
