Tried to make codes to avoid use the complex array operations. 

The basic idea is to sort intervals on the increasement of right - left + 1. Sort queries. For each interval, if any query value hits it, the answer is best. After finish the current interval, removes keys from TreeMap where query values between left and right.

Reply on java objects make the codes short. But sacrifice the time.

```
class Solution {
    public int[] minInterval(int[][] intervals, int[] queries) {
        Arrays.sort(intervals, (a, b) -> ((b[0] - a[0]) - (b[1] - a[1])));

        TreeMap<Integer, List<Integer>> treeMap = new TreeMap<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < queries.length; i++) {
            treeMap.computeIfAbsent(queries[i], a -> new ArrayList<>()).add(i);
        }

        int ret[] = new int[queries.length];
        Arrays.fill(ret, -1);
        for (int[] oneInterval : intervals) {
            int left = oneInterval[0], right = oneInterval[1];
            Map<Integer, List<Integer>> sub = treeMap.subMap(left, true, right, true);

            for (List<Integer> list : sub.values()) {
                for (int i : list) {
                    ret[i] = right - left + 1;    
                }
            }
            treeMap.keySet().removeAll(new HashSet<Integer>(sub.keySet()));
        }
        return ret;
    }
}

