# Intuition
let's say for a given query point Xi, we need to know the value of length of all the segment which inclues the point Xi in it's range i.e Li<=Xi<=Ri
# Approach
It turns out that we can do the above thing mentioned using sweep line technique. we create events array and there will be three type of events:
events of type 1: starting point of any segment 
events of type 2: Query points
events of type 3: ending point of any segment 

the events array will also have store the length of current segment, then we can simply sort the events array on increasing order of starting point and process them with a multiset which will give me length of all the segments which are currently active. (See implementation for clarity)
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
 O((N+Q)log(N+Q))
- Space complexity:
 O(N+Q)

# Code
```
#define f first
#define s second
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> minInterval(vector<vector<int>>& intervals, vector<int>& queries) {
        int q=queries.size();
        vector<int>ans(q,-1);
        vector<pair<int,pair<int,int>>>events;
        for(auto arr:intervals){
            int cost=arr[1]-arr[0]+1;
            events.push_back({arr[0],{1,cost}});
            events.push_back({arr[1],{3,cost}});
        }
        for(int i=0;i<q;i++){
            events.push_back({queries[i],{2,i}});
        }
        sort(events.begin(),events.end());
        multiset<int>ms; // maintains length of each active segment
        for(int i=0;i<events.size();i++){
            if(events[i].s.f==1){
                ms.insert(events[i].s.s);
            }else if(events[i].s.f==2){
                if(!ms.empty()){
                    ans[events[i].s.s]=*ms.begin();
                }
            }else{
                ms.erase(ms.find(events[i].s.s));
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

