# Approach
1. Sort the 2D 'intervals' array in ascending order by index 0 of every element of the 'intervals' array. 
2. Create a 2D array named 'queriesWithOriIndex' to get a copy of the 'queries' with the index of each element in the array.  
3. Sort the 'queriesWithOriIndex' array in ascending order by value(index 0) of every element of the 'queriesWithOriIndex' array.
4. Create a PriorityQueue<int[]> named minHeap to from {righti - lefti + 1, right index of current interval}
5. Run for loop and 2 while loops. 
6. Sort the 'queriesWithOriIndex' array in ascending order by index(index 1) of every element of the 'queriesWithOriIndex' array.
7. Created an array name 'result' to store index 0 of every element of the 'queriesWithOriIndex' array
8. return 'result'. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(nlog(n))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] minInterval(int[][] intervals, int[] queries) {
        // Time complexity is O(nlog(n) + qlog(q)), simplified that is O(nlog(n)), 
        // because we need to sort both in order to get the best interval and 
        // for the meat part to get the best interval, runtime just O(n). 



        // Assign the length of queries to the variable queryLength 
        // because there are several usages in the upcoming code
        int queriesLength = queries.length;

        // Sorted the intervals
        Arrays.sort(intervals, (a, b) -> (a[0] - b[0]));

        // Create a 2D array to have a record for queries with its original index
        // We must have that record in hand because the final result has to be consistent
        // with the order of elements of the original queries. 
        int[][] queriesWithOriIndex = new int[queriesLength][2];

        // After the for loop, The queriesWithOriIndex will look like:
        // [[2,0], [3,1], [4,2], [5,3]] if based on the example 1.
        // [[2,0], [19,1], [5,2], [22,3]] if based on the example 2.
        //   ↑ ↑
        //   v,i (value, index)
        for(int i=0; i<queries.length; i++) {
            queriesWithOriIndex[i] = new int[]{queries[i], i};
        }

        // BEFORE the for loop, The queriesWithOriIndex will look like:
        // [[2,0], [19,1], [5,2], [22,3]] if based on the example 2.
        // AFTER the for loop, The queriesWithOriIndex will look like:
        // [[2,0], [5,2], [19,1], [22,3]] if based on the example 2.
        // Notice that [19,1] and [5,2] is swapped because we sort it based on the index 0.
        Arrays.sort(queriesWithOriIndex, (a, b) -> (a[0] - b[0]));


        // minHeap in Java is PriorityQueue.
        // We need to specify the sort constraint because the generic type is array.
        PriorityQueue<int[]> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> (a[0]-b[0]));


        // below is the meat part I mentioned earlier, 
        // the runtime is O(n) because every interval add and poll once. 
        int j = 0; // This is for while loop use

        // The for loop is for every element insdie queriesWithOriIndex,
        // especially for index[0] of each element.
        for(int i=0; i<queriesLength; i++) {       

            // If the current query is within the left side of the interval, 
            // we add the {righti - lefti + 1, right index of the interval} into the minHeap.
            while(j<intervals.length && queriesWithOriIndex[i][0] >= intervals[j][0]) {
                int amountOfInterval = intervals[j][1] - intervals[j][0] + 1;
                int[] tempArr = new int[]{amountOfInterval, intervals[j][1]};
                minHeap.add(tempArr);
                j++;
            }

            // At this point, means we finish adding all possible intervals into minHeap, 
            // and we start to get rid of those intervals that do not fit the current query. 
            // If the current query is larger than the right side of the interval, means the 
            // current query doesn't fall into that interval, we can just poll it from
            // minHeap.
            // Notice that the next element from queriesWithOriIndex will also not 
            // falling into all the intervals we poll from minHeap because 
            // queriesWithOriIndex is sorted in ascending order.  
            // For example, if current element from queriesWithOriIndex[i][0] is 2, 
            // the upcoming element from queriesWithOriIndex[i][0] only possible that >= 2, 
            // since the current element is not fit for all those intervals, the 
            // upcoming will not fit for all those intervals as well.    
            while(!minHeap.isEmpty() && queriesWithOriIndex[i][0] > minHeap.peek()[1]) {
                minHeap.poll();
            }

            // We found the smallest interval for the query if minHeap is not empty.
            // Otherwise means we fail to find that, return -1 in this case.
            queriesWithOriIndex[i][0] = minHeap.isEmpty()?-1: minHeap.peek()[0];
        }

        // We sort the queriesWithOriIndex based on the the orginal query index. 
        Arrays.sort(queriesWithOriIndex, (a, b) -> (a[1] - b[1]));

        // And we create the result variable and run a for loop to obtain the result 
        // in the order of the original order of query. 
        int[] result = new int[queriesLength];
        for(int i=0; i<queriesLength; i++) {
            result[i] = queriesWithOriIndex[i][0];
        }

        // return result. 
        return result;
    }
}
