# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This problem can be solved efficiently with the help of lower_bound(). Lower bound returns the first element in the given data structure that is >= the passed in value.

By sorting the intervals by their size and using a set to store the queries in order, we can solve this problem in O(NLOGM) where N is the number of intervals, and M is the number of queries.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
First, sort the intervals from smallest to largest size. Then, insert all queries into a set. Also, initialize a hash table to store the size of the interval found for each query as we go.

Then, we iterate through all of our intervals and perform a binary search (using lower_bound) to find an iterator to the smallest query in our query set such that it is >= than the interval's start. Then, we use the iterator given to check if the query is within the interval's range and update our hash table to store that query's answer. We keep iterating the iterator until the query is not within the current interval's range.

Lastely, we generate our answer using the hash table that stores each query's interval size. Be sure to check if a query didn't find an interval.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N*LOGM) - N = number of intervals, M = number of queries.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(M)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    class myComp {
    public:
        bool operator()(vector<int>& i1, vector<int>& i2) {
            return i1[1] - i1[0] + 1 < i2[1] - i2[0] + 1;
        }
    };


    vector<int> minInterval(vector<vector<int>>& intervals, vector<int>& queries) {
        sort(intervals.begin(), intervals.end(), myComp()); // sort by size

        // Make set of queries
        set<int> query_set;
        for (const auto& query : queries) {
            query_set.insert(query);
        }

        unordered_map<int, int> ans = {}; // For each query, what index did we find its smallest interval at

        for (int i = 0; i < intervals.size(); ++i) {
            if (query_set.size() == 0) {
                break;
            }

            // Start at first query such that it is in this interval's range.
            // Lower bound returns the lowest value in query set such that it is >= start of interval.
            auto it = query_set.lower_bound(intervals[i][0]);
            while (it != query_set.end() && *it <= intervals[i][1]) {
                // Fits inside interval
                ans[*it] = intervals[i][1] - intervals[i][0] + 1;
                auto new_it = it;
                new_it++;
                query_set.erase(it);
                it = new_it;
            }
        }

        // Generate answer
        vector<int> ans_final;
        for (const auto& query : queries) {
            if (ans.find(query) != ans.end()) {
                ans_final.push_back(ans[query]);
            } else {
                ans_final.push_back(-1);
            }
        }

        return ans_final;
    }
};
```

