# Intuition
This problem is easy if you think that you have a dynamic pool of elegible intervals. The secret is to mantain and update that pool in a heap so to efectively select the smallest interval.

# Approach
Min heap

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n*logn)$$

- Space complexity:
$$O(n)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] minInterval(int[][] in, int[] queries) {
        Map<Integer,Integer> resp = new HashMap();
        int[] q = queries.clone();
        Arrays.sort(q);
        Queue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<int[]>((a,b)->a[1]-a[0]-(b[1]-b[0]));
        Arrays.sort(in,(a,b)->a[0]-b[0]);
        int elegible=0;
        for(int next : q) {
            if(resp.containsKey(next)) continue;
            // Add the new elegible intervals
            while(elegible<in.length&&in[elegible][0]<=next) pq.add(in[elegible++]);
            // Remove intervals that are not in range
            while(!pq.isEmpty()&&pq.peek()[1]<next) pq.remove();
            resp.put(next,pq.isEmpty()?-1:pq.peek()[1]-pq.peek()[0]+1);
        }
        int[] r = new int[q.length];
        for(int i=0;i<r.length;i++) r[i]=resp.get(queries[i]);
        return r;
    }
}
```

