# [C++] Easy to understand as a Variant of Skyline
We can treat this problem as a variant of the [Skyline problem](https://leetcode.com/problems/the-skyline-problem/).  If you're familiar with the skyline, then its solutions can easily adapted for this problem.
The main difference is that here in this problem,
we are looking for the minimum width, whereas in the skyline problem we're looking for maximum
height.

* aux data structures: 
	* enum class Kind { Start = 0, Query, End, };
	* Note that the Query is between Start and End.


Steps:
1. we convert each interval into two events (as 3-tuple/triplet):
   <start_pos, Start, height==width>,
   <end_pos,   End, height==width>,
2. each query will be converted as an event: <query_pos, Query, query_id>
3. sort the events
4. in a loop, iterate each event, and use a multiset<int> to maintain the active heights/width.
   We can get the current min height from the active heights set in O(1) time.

```
// Idea / Solution: very similar to the Skyline problem.
// The difference is that here in this problem,
// we are looking for the minimum width, whereas in the skyline problem we're looking for maximum
// height.
// aux data structures: enum class Kind { Start = 0, Query, End, }
// Steps:
// 1. we convert each interval into two events (as 3-tuple/triplet):
//    <start_pos, Start, height==width>,
//    <end_pos,   End, height==width>,
// 2. each query will be converted as an event: <query_pos, Query, query_id>
// 3. sort the events
// 4. in a loop, iterate each event, and use a multiset<int> to maintain the active heights/width.
//    We can get the current min height from the active heights set in O(1) time.
class Solution {
    /// kind of event.
    /// Objects of a Enum Class are always comparable with themselves.
    enum class Kind : int8_t {
        START = 0,
        QUERY,
        END,
    };
    using Event = tuple<int, Kind, int>;

public:
    vector<int> minInterval(vector<vector<int>>& intervals, vector<int>& queries) {
        // convert the intervals and queries into events
        vector<Event> events;
        events.reserve(intervals.size() * 2 + queries.size());
        // 1. we convert each interval into two events (as 3-tuple/triplet):
        //    <start_pos, Start, height==width>,
        //    <end_pos,   End, height==width>,
        for (auto& e : intervals) {
            auto start = e[0], end = e[1], width = end - start + 1;
            events.emplace_back(start, Kind::START, width);
            events.emplace_back(end, Kind::END, width);
        }
        // 2. each query will be converted as an event: <query_pos, Query, query_id>
        for (int q = 0; q < queries.size(); ++q) {
            events.emplace_back(queries[q], Kind::QUERY, q);
        }
        // 3. sort the events
        sort(events.begin(), events.end());
        // 4. in a loop, iterate each event, and use a multiset<int> to maintain the active
        // heights/width.
        // We can get the current min height from the active heights set in O(1) time.
        vector<int> res(queries.size(), -1);
        multiset<int> widths; // active widths
        for (auto [pos, kind, width_or_qid] : events) {
            switch (kind) {
            case Kind::START:
                widths.insert(width_or_qid);
                break;
            case Kind::QUERY:
                if (!widths.empty()) {
                    // get the current min width by querying the multiset widths.
                    res[width_or_qid] = *widths.begin();
                }
                break;
            case Kind::END:
                auto iter = widths.find(width_or_qid);
                widths.erase(iter);
                break;
            }
        }

        return res;
    }
};

```

