solutions.content:
### Sort + MinHeap

1. Sort intervals by start point
2. Sort queries (either copy queries then sort them or create a sorted query index array)
3. create a min-heap (this data strucutre is used to find the smallest size interval). In this min-heap, we use [interval size, interval end] = [r-l+1, r] as the key.
4. Iterate through queries
	a. find all intervals that contain this query and add them to the minHeap
	b. remove all invalid intervals (its right point is less than the query) from the minHeap
	c. update the result

```
public int[] minInterval(int[][] intervals, int[] queries) {
        //base case
        if(intervals == null || intervals.length == 0 || queries == null || queries.length == 0) return new int[0];

        int numOfQueries = queries.length;
        int[] result = new int[numOfQueries];

        List<Integer> sortedQueryIndex = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < numOfQueries; i++) sortedQueryIndex.add(i);


        //sort intervals base on left value (if left values are the same, sort by right value)
        Arrays.sort(intervals, (a, b) -> (a[0] == b[0] ? a[1] - b[1] : a[0] - b[0]));
        //sort queries index base on queries value [instead of sort queries, we sort the queries index]
        Collections.sort(sortedQueryIndex, (a, b)->(queries[a] - queries[b]));

        //min-heap (this data strucutre is used to find the smallest size interval)
